0.body: Welcome to the Manic Monolith: Do It Yourself book! This book will teach you the basics of the level editor, tricks and tips, and the use of ALL the objects in the game! note The book and the game are still in heavy developement, expect some things to be slightly out of date...
0.title: Introduction

1.body: One of the first thing you will have to learn is how to use the level editor UI, so this subchapter will walk you through all the stuff you need to know before you start using the level editor.
1.title: Editor UI

10.body: Another very important element of the level editor, the property editor allows you to change an object properties, like size, position, color, etc...
10.title: Property Editor

101.body: An property which defines how reflective this object is. 1 is totally reflective, and 0 doesn't reflect anything at all.
101.title: Reflectance

102.body: A Vector3 value that determies the block's linear velocity. When either the X, Y or Z values are not 0, Mart's velocity will be affected by the block's velocity. The two most important interactions are as follow but others can happen depending on which values you input. Linear Velocity has the same direction as Mart's Velocity = More velocity WHILE standing on the object! Linear Velocity has the opposite direction as Mart's Velocity = Less velocity WHILE standing on the object!
102.title: Linear velocity

103.body: A Vector3 value that determies the block's angular velocity This one is a little more complicated, and there aren't visual examples of it in action! (yet)
103.title: Angular Velocity

104.body: This object is a dynamic image which repeats in an object's surface. Not all objects can have Textures applied to them, however. For big levels, avoid using too many Textures, since they are heavier to render than Decals .
104.title: Texture

106.body: This property changes the color of the Texture, be wary that some colors wont actually change (eg.: black)
106.title: Color

107.body: Determines how far the rendered texture is offset on the horizontal axis in studs.
107.title: Offset Studs U

108.body: Determines how far the rendered texture is offset on the horizontal axis in studs.
108.title: Offset Studs V

109.body: Sets the horizontal size, in studs, of the tiled image applied by the Texture.
109.title: Studs/Tile U

11.body: THE most important feature in the entire level editor, how are you gonna make a level with no objects? Thats right, you can't! This chapter will have ALL the objects and their properties, this is intended to be used as a documentation for level creators.
11.title: Objects

110.body: Sets the vertical size, in studs, of the tiled image applied by the Texture.
110.title: Studs/Tile V

111.body: A roblox Decal ID that the Texture will use.
111.title: Image ID

112.body: A number which ranges from 0 to 1, in which 1 is fully transparent while 0 is fully opaque
112.title: Transparency

113.body: Determines the depth of the Texture relative to others. Example: Lets say that you have two Textures, and you want Decal A to be in front of Decal B, to solve that, simply set Decal A's Z Index to something higher than Decal B's Z Index.
113.title: Z Index

114.body: A property which defines what surface will this Decal be on.
114.title: Face

115.body: When you attempt to place a Texture, your mouse icon will change and elegible objects will have a missing texture image applied to them when you hover your mouse over said objects, clicking on an elegible object will place the Texture in the surface your mouse was pointing at.
115.title: Placement

116.body: 2D Trigger is an object which changes the camera to 2D mode while Mart is touching it. Every 2D Trigger has a Vector3 Value child which holds the camera axis override
116.title: 2D Trigger

117.body: All 2D Triggers have a Vector 3 Value child which determines the camera axis override. warning There are only two stable axis overrides, those are 1, 1, 0 or 0, 1, 1. All other axis override combinations are unstable and should not be used.
117.title: Remarks

12.body: An Attachment is used to store a position relative to its parent, for example, every Lap 2 object will have an Attachment as its child, said attachment points to the position Mart is going to be teleported when he touches the Lap 2 object.
12.title: Attachment

120.body: This property can only be edited with the position handle. Its value will be where the 2D Trigger is in the level.
120.title: Positioning

121.body: This object cannot be placed, instead its a child of objects. This object has one purpose: hold a number value
121.title: Number Value

124.body: This object cannot be placed, instead its a child of objects. This object has one purpose: hold a vector3 value
124.title: Vector 3 Value

14.body: This property can only be edited with the position handle. Its value will be where the Attachment is relative to its parent
14.title: Positioning

15.body: When you attempt to place an Attachment in the level, your mouse icon will change and elegible objects will gain a orange-ish outline on them, click on an elegible object and the attachment will be placed as a child of that object.
15.title: Placing

16.body: Birby is an enemy with no behaviour, its just static object that can be killed.
16.title: Birby

18.body: This property can only be edited through with the position/rotation handles. Its value is simply where Birby is in the level.
18.title: Positioning

19.body: Its a solid block which breaks when Mart collides with it at reasonably slow speeds. Grabbing breaks them, so does groundpounding/divebombing on them.
19.title: Breakable Block (weak)

2.body: One of the core elements of the UI, its simple, but you will be using this very often. Its composed of various buttons each with a different function.
2.breadcrumbs: Introduction » Editor UI » The options bar
2.title: The options bar

21.body: Determines the breakable block's size note The block's durability won't change with size! Its best to just have a long sequence of individual breakable blocks if you thought of doing that!
21.title: Size

22.body: Determines the breakable block's position in the level
22.title: Positioning

25.body: A number which can range from 0 to 1, the bigger the number the more reflective the block is, at 1 it's fully reflective, like glass, and at 0 it doesn't reflect anything at all.
25.title: Reflectance

26.body: A number which ranges from 0 to 1, 1 is fully transparent while 0 is fully opaque.
26.title: Transparency

27.body: A Vector3 value that determies the block's linear velocity. When either the X, Y or Z values are not 0, Mart's velocity will be affected by the block's velocity. The two most important interactions are as follow but others can happen depending on which values you input. Linear Velocity has the same direction as Mart's Velocity = More velocity WHILE standing on the object! Linear Velocity has the opposite direction as Mart's Velocity = Less velocity WHILE standing on the object!
27.title: Linear velocity

28.body: A Vector3 value that determies the block's angular velocity This one is a little more complicated, and there aren't visual examples of it in action! (yet)
28.title: Angular Velocity

29.body: Its a solid block which breaks when Mart collides with it at high speeds. Groundpounds/divebombs dont break this block unless Mart is going past a certain vertical speed.
29.title: Breakable Block (strong)

3.body: Its the ">" button, it just hides the options bar so that you can have more screen space.
3.title: Hide button

31.body: Determines the breakable block's size note The block's durability won't change with size! Its best to just have a long sequence of individual breakable blocks if you thought of doing that!
31.title: Size

32.body: Determines the breakable block's position in the level
32.title: Positioning

35.body: A number which can range from 0 to 1, the bigger the number the more reflective the block is, at 1 it's fully reflective, like glass, and at 0 it doesn't reflect anything at all.
35.title: Reflectance

36.body: A number which ranges from 0 to 1, 1 is fully transparent while 0 is fully opaque.
36.title: Transparency

37.body: A Vector3 value that determies the block's linear velocity. When either the X, Y or Z values are not 0, Mart's velocity will be affected by the block's velocity. The two most important interactions are as follow but others can happen depending on which values you input. Linear Velocity has the same direction as Mart's Velocity = More velocity WHILE standing on the object! Linear Velocity has the opposite direction as Mart's Velocity = Less velocity WHILE standing on the object!
37.title: Linear velocity

38.body: A Vector3 value that determies the block's angular velocity This one is a little more complicated, and there aren't visual examples of it in action! (yet)
38.title: Angular Velocity

39.body: Its a collectible which increases the player's score then they touch Mart.
39.title: Coin

4.body: When pressed it teleports you to the main game where your level is instantly loaded after the loading screen finishes You can't playtest your level if your level settings are invalid If you haven't saved your level, the playtest button will give you a warning and do nothing.
4.title: Playtest

41.body: This property can only be edited with the position/rotation handles. Its value will be where the coin is in the level.
41.title: Positioning

42.body: This property is a number that ranges from 0 to 1, in which 1 is fully transparent while 0 is fully opaque.
42.title: Transparency

43.body: Its a collectible which increases the player's score then they touch Mart. This object behaves almost identically to the Coin , but this one can only be collected during Manic Mania.
43.title: Coin (Manic Mania)

45.body: This property can only be edited with the position/rotation handles. Its value will be where the coin is in the level.
45.title: Positioning

46.body: This property is a number that ranges from 0 to 1, in which 1 is fully transparent while 0 is fully opaque.
46.title: Transparency

47.body: This object is a static image which is stretched into an object's surface. Not all objects can have Decals applied to them, however. For big levels, try to use Decals when possible instead of Textures , since its more lightweight on the player's device.
47.title: Decal

49.body: This property changes the color of the decal, be wary that some colors wont actually change (eg.: black)
49.title: Color

5.body: Another very important element of the level editor, when pressed, a vertical bar will appear at the left side of the screen, displaying all of the objects you can place in a level Clicking on an object puts it in your mouse cursor, from there, drag your mouse at the place you want to put the object an simply click with the left mouse button, 🎉 You have placed your first object!
5.title: Objects

50.body: A roblox Decal ID that the Decal will use.
50.title: Image ID

51.body: A number which ranges from 0 to 1, in which 1 is fully transparent while 0 is fully opaque
51.title: Transparency

52.body: Determines the depth of the texture relative to others. Example: Lets say that you have two Decals, and you want Decal A to be in front of Decal B, to solve that, simply set Decal A's Z Index to something higher than Decal B's Z Index.
52.title: Z Index

53.body: A property which defines what surface will this Decal be on.
53.title: Face

54.body: When you attempt to place a Decal, your mouse icon will change and elegible objects will have a missing texture decal applied to them when you hover your mouse over said objects, clicking on an elegible object will place the decal in the surface your mouse was pointing at.
54.title: Placement

55.body: This object ends the level when touched during Manic Mania. caution An Escape object is essential for a level, as there is no way of finishing a level (successfully) without it!
55.title: Escape

57.body: This property can only be edited with the position/rotation handle. Its value will be where the Escape object is in the level.
57.title: Positioning

58.body: A property which defines the Escape object's color.
58.title: Color

59.body: The Lap 2 object teleports Mart to where its Attachment child points to. important A Lap 2 object is essential for a level, since the player can't get a P rank without it.
59.title: Lap 2

6.body: Its where you tweak your level behavior, like the amount of points needed for each rank, level track ID, level name ETC...
6.title: Level Settings

60.body: This object has an Attachment as a child, the Attachment 's position will be used to determine where Mart will get teleported after starting Lap 2
60.title: Remarks

62.body: This property can only be edited with the position handle. Its value will be where the Lap 2 object is in the level.
62.title: Positioning

63.body: A property which defines this object's color.
63.title: Color

64.body: This object starts Manic Mania when touched, this object also gives points and a combo boost when touched. caution A Manic Mania Cube object is essential for a level since there is no way of triggering Manic Mania without one of those.
64.breadcrumbs: Objects » Manic Mania Cube » Manic Mania Cube
64.title: Manic Mania Cube

66.body: This property can only be edited with the position handle. Its value will be where the Manic Mania Cube is in the level
66.title: Positioning

67.body: This object inherits all the properties from the Stud object, but this one can only collide with Mart during Manic Mania.
67.breadcrumbs: Objects » Manic Mania Stud (collide) » Manic Mania Stud (collide)
67.title: Manic Mania Stud (collide)

69.body: This property can only be edited with the position/rotation handle.
69.title: Positioning

7.body: When clicked, an view of all the objects in the current level will show in a tree like hierarchy. Clicking on an object will select it.
7.title: Object Tree

72.body: Determines this object's shape. Those shapes are: Ball A spherical shape. Block A block shape. Cylinder A cylinder shape. Wedge A wedge shape with a slope on one side. Corner Wedge A wedge shape with slopes on two sides.
72.title: Shape

8.body: Allows you to save, load and erase your levels. You can also: Save a level as new level (you won't overwrite any levels you already got) Load a new empty level

87.body: An secret object has a Number Value as it child. When Mart touches this object, he gets teleported into the secret tied with the Number Value 's Value property. If mart touches this object while already in a secret, he gets sent back to the secret he first went through.
87.title: Secret

88.body: This object has a Number Value as its child, this Number Value , stores a value ranging from 1 to 3, this value must be unique between all secrets in the main level.
88.title: Remarks

9.body: It changes the current view of your level when clicked. The order goes by (it loops back to the first view mode) Level Mode: Its the default mode, you can only see and edit the main world (where Mart spawns) Secret 1-3 Mode: All those are like the Level Mode, but you can only see and edit their respective secrets.
9.breadcrumbs: Introduction » Editor UI » Current View Toggle
9.title: Current View Toggle

90.body: This property can only be edited with the position handle. Its value will be where the Secret is in the level.
90.title: Positioning

91.body: This object defines Mart's spawn position in the level. It also defines where mart will appear after going through a Secret in the main level. caution This object is essential for a level, as levels without one will just refuse to load.
91.title: Spawnpoint

93.body: This property can only be edited with the position handle. Its value will be where the Spawnpoint is in the level
93.title: Positioning

94.body: The Stud is the most important object in the entire level object, its the most basic bulding block one can use.
94.title: Stud

96.body: This property can only be edited with the position/rotation handle.
96.title: Positioning
